annotation:
Both sides are improving their pieces' position, and Black still looks a bit better, but I wasn't sure what to do. So I played this very useful multi-purpose move, which achieves 3 useful things:

1) The knight is moving towards c5, where it will put pressure on white's light-squared bishop and target White's b3-pawn;
2) It unblocks Black's dark-squared bishop, which can start to put pressure on the long diagonal;
3) It allows Black to play f7-f5, which will gain more space in the centre and kingside (a typical plan in the KID), as well as preventing White's knight from landing on the strong e4-square.
